UTF-8 vs UTF-16 vs. UTF-32

BOM vs little endian vs big endian.

BOM (byte order mark)

prerequesite:

create a basic gradle project
`gradle init`
> options: basic, groovy DSL, neovim-test

`touch Main.kt`
where the locale settings are as following:
```
$ locale
LANG=de_DE.utf8
LANGUAGE=
LC_CTYPE="de_DE.utf8"
LC_NUMERIC="de_DE.utf8"
LC_TIME="de_DE.utf8"
LC_COLLATE="de_DE.utf8"
LC_MONETARY="de_DE.utf8"
LC_MESSAGES="de_DE.utf8"
LC_PAPER="de_DE.utf8"
LC_NAME="de_DE.utf8"
LC_ADDRESS="de_DE.utf8"
LC_TELEPHONE="de_DE.utf8"
LC_MEASUREMENT="de_DE.utf8"
LC_IDENTIFICATION="de_DE.utf8"
LC_ALL=
```

```
$ file -i Main.kt
Main.kt: inode/x-empty; charset=binary
```

insert text into it and save it.
> note that the language server was already working, capabilities were UTF-8 and
> UTF-16

```
$ iconv -f US-ASCII -t UTF-8 -o Main2.kt Main.kt 
$ file -i Main2.kt
Main2.kt: text/x-c++; charset=us-ascii
```

Change did not work appropriate.
Lets create the file within nvim. 
> note that `:verbose set encoding` outputs `encoding=utf-8`
> note that `:verbose set fileencoding` outputs `fileencoding=utf-8`

`file -i FromNvim.kt` prompts the similiar result.

